Since 1987 the Catholic Church has provided financial as well as technical support to a private clinic, La Casa del Encargo familiar, which serves as a referral center for abortion services for women in Nicaragua. However, even medical abortions performed at private clinics require authorization from several medical and government officials.

Critics of abortion laws have pointed out that these laws:" emphasize the needs of fetuses but often minimize the rights of women… and [are] thus of questionable constitutionality‖ (Pierotti, 2002:270). Anti-choice advocates continue to argue that the anti-abortion laws in Nicaragua and other similar countries force women to continue unwanted pregnancies that put the women, the fetuses and others at risk of suffering physical or psychological damage. Despite pro-life groups and opposition from the Catholic Church some Nicaraguan activists have urged the health ministry to consider issuing safe abortion prescriptions along with other medications.
